From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000018 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Jun 2026 12:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] regulator: ti-abb: report -ENOTRECOVERABLE before first set

ti_abb_get_voltage_sel() returns abb->current_info_idx, which is -EINVAL until
the first ti_abb_set_voltage_sel() (the ABB LDO bias is unknown at probe). When
the abb node carries regulator-min/max constraints -- needed so a consumer can
drive the body bias via regulator_set_voltage() -- the regulator core reads the
voltage during registration (machine_constraints_voltage, apply_uV path) and gets
that negative selector, so the regulator fails to register with -EINVAL.

The core already handles this case for "regulators that can't be read and must be
initialized": if get_voltage returns -ENOTRECOVERABLE it applies the constraint
voltage instead of failing. So report -ENOTRECOVERABLE while current_info_idx is
unset, letting the core initialise the ABB to the constraint voltage (bypass).
Needed on OMAP4460 (Nexus Q) where the cpu-supply drives FBB at OPP-Nitro.

Signed-off-by: Petr Parkan Janda <petronijus@bastla.com>
---
--- a/drivers/regulator/ti-abb-regulator.c	2026-06-26 11:18:30.706290548 +0200
+++ b/drivers/regulator/ti-abb-regulator.c	2026-06-26 11:18:51.537971560 +0200
@@ -396,6 +396,19 @@
 		return -EINVAL;
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * Until the first ti_abb_set_voltage_sel(), current_info_idx is -EINVAL --
+	 * the ABB LDO bias is unknown, not yet selected. Report that as
+	 * -ENOTRECOVERABLE so the regulator core initialises us (applies the
+	 * constraint voltage) rather than failing registration. This matters when a
+	 * consumer drives the body bias and the abb node therefore carries
+	 * regulator-min/max constraints (which makes the core read the voltage at
+	 * registration); without it ti_abb returns a negative selector and the
+	 * regulator fails to register.
+	 */
+	if (abb->current_info_idx < 0)
+		return -ENOTRECOVERABLE;
+
 	return abb->current_info_idx;
 }
 
